OOC The series that follows explores the dynamics of enemies ... and may at times contain adult themes...so be forewarned... <br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Selilya had finally made the decision to visit the new land. She detested the cold, but had heard many positive reports of the untapped wealth to be had. The Violent Harvest had even been invited to join General Zirrix T'Rhennic in a hunt. He proposed warring against the spiteful Coldain in an effort to forge an alliance with a previouly unseen tribe of followers of Rallos Zek. <br>
<br>
Some of the Harvest had already journeyed to the new land and had whetted her appetite with stories of amazing creatures to hunt, new peoples to conquer, and treasures unseen previously. She wanted to investigate these Coldain herself to ascertain why the General found destroying them so palatable. She was not adverse to killing dwarfs, in fact, she relished the opportunity. <br>
<br>
Her husband, Ernseax, had healed nicely from the wounds he received from his misadventure in Guk, and he had already left for the hunt again, leaving her alone once more. Perhaps it was for the best anyway, for her duties as Winnower had priority in carrying out the will of the Father. <br>
<br>
She completed furnishing her backpack and extinguished the lanterns in the cottage. With a lingering glance over the cottage she called home, she tried to drink in all the images of warmth to sustain her for the cold, dark trip ahead. <br>
<br>
She met Dephiler at the entrance to Neriak. He had offered to transport her to the new land. He was a rather new recruit to the Harvest, but she instantly saw the raging fire of hate burning within him and knew he had found his place amongst the Chosen. <br>
<br>
&quot;Winnower, you will want to cast invisibilty on yourself. Oh, and be ready to fight,&quot; he snickered. &quot;It can sometimes be...well...a rude arrival.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Indeed?&quot; she asked. &quot;Well, this sounds like fun&quot; <br>
<br>
Dephiler cast his magics and within seconds they had appeared at the teleportation spot. Dephiler bowed and wished Selilya a safe journey. <br>
<br>
&quot;I wish you had brought an escort, Winnower. Your safety is always our concern,&quot; he stated. <br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, I know, my friend. I think I will do better alone. I won't be worrying about any parties.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;As you wish.&quot; Dephiler chanted his spell and was gone in a flash. <br>
<br>
&quot;My, it is cold,&quot; she uttered, as she pulled her cloak tightly around herself. <br>
<br>
She gazed at the sights before her. It was a land of white...in all directions. The creatures she saw were truly amazing. It was almost joyful to her to see such wonders....yet she kept a tight fist on her staff just in case. This was not a place where she wanted to meet her end. <br>
<br>
Ahead in the distance, she saw the dragon bridge. It had  been described to her in countless reports, but nothing could take the place of witnessing it in person. Her gawk was short-lived, as she saw some of the more vicious tenants of the land heading her way. Not wanting to engage in battle so soon, she hastened her steps past the giant on watch and made her way across. <br>
<br>
As she stepped off the bridge she scanned the horizon before her. Again, rolling nolls of white in every direction. It would be easy to get lost here, she observed, and she was grateful she had such keenly developed navigational skills. She wanted to pass through these Eastern Wastes quickly. She didn't want to be out here when night fell. <br>
<br>
She checked her flimsy map once again and set out towards the valley leading to the Great Divide. It was difficult for her not to linger and explore the new structures she saw. She saw some Coldain and some Orcs even...and she steered clear. No, she had to press on. There would be another time...and she made her way into the Great Divide. <br>
<br>
Selilya decided to sit for a moment and nibble on a fishcake she had brought and take a drink of water. She again gazed on the the terrain before her before setting off. She knew from her map that Thurgadin would be off to her right. So she warily set off in that direction but then paused. Supposedly this was also where wurms abode as well. She was most curious to espy one and decided it would be just a slight delay in her trip to head to the wurm caves. There were some steeper hills and more boulders visible as she neared the caves. <br>
<br>
She observed a group of hunters off in the trees, knowing they were waiting to snare a wurm. Not wanting to distract them she made her way atop the wurm cave to cross over to the other side of the stream undetected. She knew the waters would be most unpleasant should she choose to wade across, so she took a quick survey of the shoreline...and then she saw what she was looking for. Not far upstream were six smooth boulders jutting out of the water's surface. These would be perfect for the brief hop to the other side. <br>
<br>
She was halfway across when a Guardian Shardwurm roared behind her, the very force of its blast knocking her into the icy water. Selilya's mind didn't register the shock to her system. She was scrambling away to avoid the sharp claws. Unfortunately she felt the flesh in her shoulder being ripped viciously by one one its talons. Her body shook violently when she plummeted into the snow drift trying to evade the monster behind her. She barely heard the shouts of the closing hunting party as they taunted the wurm away from her. <br>
<br>
Then the snow began to fall...and the wind seemed to howl in gale fury from the north. Despite the sharp pain and biting cold that tore into her consciousness, she knew she had to get up and make her way to Thurgadin. An icy death awaited her if she failed to find warmth soon. <br>
<br>
Blinded by the stinging shards of icy snow, she pressed on in the direction she felt would lead her to the city. She stumbled on rocks and slipped on icy patches of earth. The minutes seemed to become hours. Soon, there was utter silence. The blizzard left as quickly as it had come...and Selilya had wandered... <br>
<br>
Terrified, she quickly assessed her situation. She was trembling from the biting elements and quite lost. To top it all off...she was perched upon a minor cliff... and, although a fall would not result in death, it would be most painful. She began to look for a way down. <br>
<br>
Her eyes began to focus on the terrain below. And there he was. Of all places to encounter an enemy, he was here. The barbarian, McMad. She must have made quite a ruckus as she was trying to orient herself, because he was glaring at her even now. <br>
<br>
&quot;Ha!&quot; he cried. &quot;You still spy on me, dark one?&quot; He seemed to gloat. In that moment, however, he failed to see the pair of dire wolves approaching him from the rear. <br>
<br>
&quot;McMad! Behind you!&quot; Selilya screamed...without even knowing why. She began to take a step forward to see if she'd been heard...and then the cliff gave way. <br>
<br>
Her whole existence seemed to come to a crawl as images of seasons before flashed through her mind. She tumbled headlong into darkness...her head finding its resting place on a boulder at the bottom of the precipe. <br>
